description: Tim Cullinan  added  3 new photos . I've never seen a fisher (Pekania pennanti) in the wild. It is perhaps the most elusive mammal in the northern forests. This summer I've been helping the National Park Service survey for them in the Olympic Mountains.  Two weeks ago I led a crew into a remote area to set up bait stations monitored by automatic motion-sensor cameras. We didn't have high hopes that we would find anything. Fishers have been perilously close to extinction in this region for half a century.  Yesterday our crew hiked back in to check our cameras, and...Eureka!

description: Tim Cullinan Our local Peregrine Falcons nest above timberline in the nearby mountains. After their young have fledged, they no longer need the security of the rocky cliffs, so the family migrates down to the lowlands where there’s more prey available. In the past few years the parents have discovered that the open-topped Douglas-fir tree in our backyard is a good place to park their youngsters while they patrol the beach (about a quarter mile away) where the shorebirds are fat and plentiful. The juveniles sit in the tree and scream for food (sounds like some kids I know). Sometimes the parents bring them food, but they’re entering the season when the adults are teaching the juveniles to hunt. So they circle the neighborhood, encouraging the young to take the food while airborne. I took this video from our back porch this evening.

description: Bob Michel Tuneful Ersatz Thursday!  I have rolled my eyes at the clueless comments, barely swallowed snarky comebacks to the tasteless requests. I have cringed at the demeaning t-shirts and shuddered at the annual brogues. I have threaded my way through so many puking tangles of fake-ID heroes on the late train home that the mere word "Villanova" inspires in me a sort of Pavlovian panic. For what it's worth I'm half-Irish myself--all year round--and I've played the damn music most of my life. So I've been there, folks.  Half-Irish, but also purebred contrarian. And so, flipping the coin over to glance at its other side, I reflect--with a tip o' the hat to cousin  Tim , who pointed this out to me--that the name of my mother's mother, Anna Mary Connolly of Loughrea, is inscribed on the European Immigrant Wall of Honor at Ellis Island just below that of one Pasquale Connola. A chance juxtaposition which warms me to the depths of my Yank soul.  I love the pure drop, you see, and bristle--like you--when it's cheapened and adulterated in silly, tawdry, commercial ways. But as a thorough child of the New World I also love all that's been melted, mottled and mongrelized. Authenticity is grand, mind. But so, in its way, is this:  Take a German composer and a couple of New England-bred lyricists, give them an out-of-tune upright on West 28th St., a deadline and a template of vague nostalgia ("I know--Dixie! No, wait; we did Dixie last week..."), sprinkle on a few...I don't know, shamrocks, roses, lakes, dells, vales, rills...they know the drill, and they can knock this off before lunch. And--faith and begorrah!--didn't it just become the #1 hit (by some accounts) of...wait for it...1916?  My point being? Well, that this, too, for better or worse, is where I come from. So rather than grouse about plastic paddies today, I'll just put on my vaudeville hat and share a wee scrap of my country's traditional music.  Top o' the mornin' to y'all! This one's for Anna Mary. And for Pasquale.

description: Tim Cullinan Two days ago the Northwest lost one of our native treasures. Phil Williams, musician, teacher, historian, and mentor to countless guitarists, passed away in Seattle.  Phil and his wife Vivian have been playing, teaching and preserving traditional music in the Northwest for the better part of a century. Forty years ago they founded Voyager Records, an effort to record and preserve the traditional music of our region. Both were founders of the Northwest Folklife Festival and of the Washington Old-Time Fiddlers Association. Phil was a renowned music historian, and was a consultant to the Smithsonian regarding the history of traditional music in the Northwest.  I could never make up my mind which had a richer sound, Phil’s baritone voice or his 1930s vintage Martin guitar. Either way, listening to Phil and Vivian in concert was a unique treat. They often prefaced their performances with historical information about the origin of the tune they were about to play. Phil always seemed to have some quirky story about how they discovered the tune.  The clip below is a case in point, and also illustrates Phil’s genius as a back-up guitarist for old time fiddle tunes. Listen to his runs and walk-downs, and note his left hand—it never stops moving. Phil’s style influenced hundreds, if not thousands, of traditional musicians in the Northwest.  So long Phil. We’ll miss you.

description: Tim Cullinan  added  11 new photos . It's late winter, so I'm conducting my biennial ritual of capturing Roosevelt elk and tagging them with GPS tracking collars. This is part of a long-term research project to learn more about the demographics, home range and habitat use of elk herds in two river valleys on the eastern slope of the Olympic Mountains in Washington.  This year, to avoid a two-hour daily commute, I'm living five days a week in a cabin at the study site. My kitchen window looks up the narrow Duckabush river valley, and affords some spectacular views--when I'm home long enough to enjoy them.  Here are a few shots from this week's work...

description: Tim Cullinan  added  12 new photos . Today marks my tenth anniversary of being hired as the Wildlife Program Manager for the S’Klallam Indian Tribes of northwest Washington.  I wasn’t the least bit apprehensive about ending my comfortable 18-year tenure with a wildlife conservation non-profit and making the leap to Indian Country. It was time for a change, and I couldn’t have chosen a better path.  The S’Klallams like to say that they have lived here “since time immemorial.” Some of the ancient village sites have been dated at more than 4,000 years old, and it’s likely they were here much longer. The discovery and radio-carbon dating of a bone spear point, embedded in the fossilized remains of a mastodon found a few miles from my home, confirm that aboriginal people have been hunting on this coastal plain for at least 13,600 years. It is an honor to be entrusted by the S’Klallams to manage the wild resources that are such an integral part of their culture.  My transition from my twenty-first century western culture into the world of the S’Klallams was seamless. From the first day, they extended to me the warmest of welcomes. I’ve been made to feel like part of the family.  This has been good for me.

description: Carol Cullinane Larry Cullinane   Tim Cullinan  My great-grandfather, Patrick Kelly fought with the Connaught Rangers and died of  wounds fighting WW1. He was Irish. He became a soldier and Ireland, let's not forget, was part of the Brithish Empire at the time, and this gave him a wage and his wife an allowance!!! Important elementsand factors at that time!!!  The Great War, World War I was declared and he did, as solidiers were ordered to do,  fight!. Was he really aware against whom or what? Who knows?   He fought, he was wounded, he was discharged, although badly wounded, and continued to fight... after all he was a solider. For 60 days he endured this until he eventually succumbed to his wounds. He died on 3rd November 1914,in what is known as the First Battle for Ypres, Belgium,   So where am I going with this? Yes I would like to wear a poppy in his honour but up to now it has all  felt a bit too British which is something I don't relate to, it all seems a bit too Commonwealth for my liking!! (with all my respects to the Commonwealth!)  On the other hand I have always felt guilty about not supporting the  Connaught Rangers  or commemorating my Great Grandfather so I totally admire and support  Leo Varadkar T.D.  in helping the Irish to honour their ancesters while being proud to be Irish.  With  # ArmisticeDay   coming up on the 11th of November I would like to wear a   # ShamrockPoppy  (can someone send me on one?) and show my pride and respect for all those Irish soldiers, and all other nationalities, who died during WWI. RIP.
